---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Container from "@/components/container.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Cohort-Based Courses: A Complete Guide"
  description="Everything you need to know about cohort-based courses (CBCs) - from what they are, how to build them, and why they're transforming online education."
>
  <Container>
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-16 md:py-24">
      <!-- Hero -->
      <div class="mb-12">
        <a href="/resources" class="text-sm text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700 mb-4 inline-block">← Back to Resources</a>
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Cohort-Based Courses</h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-slate-600 mb-6">
          A comprehensive guide to understanding, building, and running cohort-based courses that transform learners.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
          <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-blue-50 text-blue-700 text-sm font-medium rounded-full">Active Learning</span>
          <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-blue-50 text-blue-700 text-sm font-medium rounded-full">Community-Driven</span>
          <span class="px-3 py-1 bg-blue-50 text-blue-700 text-sm font-medium rounded-full">80-90% Completion</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Table of Contents -->
      <nav class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6 mb-12">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Table of Contents</h2>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
          <li><a href="#what-are-cbcs" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">What are Cohort-Based Courses?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#three-attributes" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">The Three Essential Attributes</a></li>
          <li><a href="#getting-started" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">How to Get Started Building a CBC</a></li>
          <li><a href="#vs-moocs" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">CBCs vs MOOCs</a></li>
          <li><a href="#vs-universities" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">CBCs vs Traditional Universities</a></li>
          <li><a href="#tailwinds" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">Current Tailwinds Making CBCs Popular</a></li>
          <li><a href="#future" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">Where CBCs Are Headed</a></li>
          <li><a href="#platform-providers" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">What CBC Platform Providers Do</a></li>
          <li><a href="#core-areas" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">Core Focus Areas for Platforms</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-can-build" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">Who Can Build a Good CBC?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#instructor-roles" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">Roles of a CBC Instructor</a></li>
          <li><a href="#market-evolution" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">How the Space Is Evolving</a></li>
          <li><a href="#key-players" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">Key Players in the CBC Space</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references" class="text-blue-600 hover:text-blue-700">References & Further Reading</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>

      <!-- Content -->
      <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">

        <section id="what-are-cbcs" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">What are Cohort-Based Courses?</h2>

          <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-blue-600 pl-4 italic text-slate-700 my-6">
            "Cohort-based courses are so powerful because they occupy the middle ground between content and consulting. They combine the scalability and quality control of a product with the personalization and intimacy of a service."
          </blockquote>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            Cohort-based courses (CBCs) represent a fundamental shift in online education—moving away from passive content consumption toward active, community-driven learning experiences that drive real transformation.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="three-attributes" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">The Three Essential Attributes</h2>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6">For an online course to be truly cohort-based, it must satisfy three core attributes:</p>

          <div class="space-y-8">
            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">1. Time-Bound</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                Just like courses in a regular university, CBCs are time-bound. They have a well-defined start date and end date. A cohort selected from a large pool of applicants commences their learning together on a particular date, with the intent of achieving their learning outcomes by a particular date.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">2. Active Learning</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
                Regular university courses are primarily lecture-driven. Lectures, just like MOOCs, are all about passive content consumption. CBCs, however, aren't based entirely around passive content consumption.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-700 mb-3 font-semibold">Active learning includes:</p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700">
                <li>Learning by doing</li>
                <li>Hands-on engagement</li>
                <li>Project-based learning</li>
                <li>Peer engagement - Debates, discussions, group chats and DMs</li>
                <li>Feedback from coaches</li>
                <li>Feedback from peers</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-slate-700 mt-4">
                <strong>Example:</strong> Instead of reading about sales, in a CBC a student is made to do an actual sales pitch with the coach role-playing as a client. The student is then encouraged to iterate and attempt the pitch again. With Q&A, discussions, debates with peers and role-playing, CBCs are far more engaging than regular courses.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">3. Community</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
                Every CBC comes with a dedicated community of like-minded peers who are co-learners. Since learning is an interactive, iterative process—debating with a friend, hashing out ideas, being inspired by someone—all of this is part of the learning process.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                Communities present opportunities for students to connect with peers who share their interests. It presents an opportunity for a group of students to develop their own shorthand and shared experiences that gradually help them form a close-knit group.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="getting-started" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">How to Get Started Building a CBC</h2>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            To get started, it's best to define the student transformation you're seeking and capture it as 'Course Objectives'. Focus on questions like:
          </p>

          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 mb-6">
            <li>What is the student leaving with after the course?</li>
            <li>What can the student do now that they couldn't do at the beginning of the course?</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            Once that's clearly defined, start working backward from that point.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 p-4 my-6">
            <p class="text-sm text-amber-900 font-semibold mb-2">Important Note:</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-amber-800">
              Cohort-based courses should ideally pre-select for students who are at the same level in terms of their prior knowledge. Mixing up students who are not at the same level tends to be quite problematic.
            </p>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 mt-8">Key Factors to Consider</h3>

          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 mb-6">
            <li><strong>Duration:</strong> How long should the course be? (Can range from half a day to 6 months)</li>
            <li><strong>Pricing:</strong> What is the course pricing?</li>
            <li><strong>Student count threshold:</strong> What works at 10-20 students won't work at 50-60 students, which won't work at 100-200 students. Completely new strategies are needed at 500-1000 students.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 mt-8">Course Structure</h3>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">The course should be a mix of:</p>

          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 mb-6">
            <li>Asynchronous and synchronous sessions</li>
            <li>Group-work and self-work</li>
            <li>Project-based activities</li>
            <li>Community-based activities</li>
            <li>Less lecture-based passive content consumption</li>
            <li>More practical-tactical-knowledge building work and hands-on activities</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="text-slate-700">
            There are several permutations and combinations possible—courses can be entirely project-driven or a combination of lecture and project-driven approaches.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="vs-moocs" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">How CBCs Are Better Than MOOCs</h2>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            With MOOCs, you have access to lectures by all the best professors in the world. But the downside is there's no accountability, no forcing function that helps you stick with a topic long enough to learn it thoroughly.
          </p>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
            <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-900 mb-3">MOOCs</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-red-800">
                <li>• <strong>6-7% completion rate</strong></li>
                <li>• No accountability mechanisms</li>
                <li>• Passive content consumption</li>
                <li>• Limited engagement hooks</li>
                <li>• No peer pressure or support</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-green-900 mb-3">CBCs</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-green-800">
                <li>• <strong>80-90% completion rate</strong></li>
                <li>• Built-in accountability</li>
                <li>• Active learning & practice</li>
                <li>• Multiple engagement tactics</li>
                <li>• Positive peer pressure</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            Most learning is not easy. Students need to apply themselves, think deeply, and undertake difficult challenges. They need support for the emotional labor required, especially during harder parts of the learning cycle.
          </p>

          <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-blue-600 pl-4 italic text-slate-700 my-6">
            "With enough intrinsic motivation, explicit knowledge can usually be learned async via videos/text. But tacit knowledge comes from practice, which is 10x easier to accumulate in sufficient quantities to turn into skills in the context of a structured cohort."
          </blockquote>

          <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-4 my-6">
            <p class="text-sm text-blue-900 font-semibold mb-2">Prediction:</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-blue-800">
              The market for self-paced MOOC courses in the few hundred dollar range will be decimated in the next few years. They lack the affordability/simplicity of a book and the community/accountability of cohort-based courses.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="vs-universities" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">How Online CBCs Are Better Than Traditional Universities</h2>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">Universities come with significant friction to actual learning:</p>

          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 mb-6">
            <li><strong>Cost prohibitive:</strong> Tuition fees create barriers for many learners</li>
            <li><strong>Location dependent:</strong> Limited by geography and local institutions</li>
            <li><strong>Limited instructor quality:</strong> Restricted to who's available locally</li>
            <li><strong>Inflexible scheduling:</strong> Fixed schedules don't work for working professionals</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="text-slate-700">
            With CBCs, the removal of location limitations and associated cost reductions make for a much more enriching and accessible learning experience.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="tailwinds" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Current Tailwinds Making CBCs More Popular</h2>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">The Pandemic Effect</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            One of the biggest factors that pushed forward CBCs was the pandemic. It accelerated digital adoption and changed how people view online learning.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 mt-6">Key Shifts</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 mb-6">
            <li>People are increasingly comfortable meeting, communicating, and learning online</li>
            <li>Companies are shifting to remote-only workforces</li>
            <li>Greater openness to video communication</li>
            <li>People have learned how to build community and relationships online</li>
            <li>Tools like Discord and Slack are now common, even outside tech circles</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6 my-6">
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-700 mb-3">
              <strong>Note:</strong> There's nothing new about CBCs as an approach toward teaching—it's actually the most primitive model of teaching. The difference is that cohort-based teaching has now moved completely online, which presents both new challenges and opportunities.
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 italic">
              At Pupilfirst, we ran our first cohort-based course back in 2015, with coaches, students, teaching assistants, and operations teams all distributed.
            </p>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 mt-6">Other Megatrends</h3>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700">
            <li>Rising lack of trust toward university credentialism</li>
            <li>Faster internet speeds globally</li>
            <li>Cheaper computers and storage</li>
            <li>Better mobile devices</li>
            <li>Better web browsers and tools</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="future" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Where CBCs Are Headed</h2>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            As the next major step in the evolution of online learning, CBCs are further democratizing access to teaching and learning. Professors, subject matter experts, and skilled individuals from all domains will enter the creator economy.
          </p>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            <strong>We're still in the very early days of CBCs</strong>—there's tremendous collective innovation and creativity yet to emerge in this segment.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3 mt-6">Unlocking Hidden Expertise</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            One amazing possibility: There are many subject matter experts (SMEs), highly skilled practitioners, and seasoned operators who are not teaching others yet. They are well-respected in their micro-communities but don't have an audience beyond it. They've been silently working on their craft, sharpening their skills, but not actively teaching in a structured manner.
          </p>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            Getting these individuals to start their online CBCs will help others who don't have access to these experts learn from them and innovate in their local domains. These tutors can showcase what excellence looks like, share their tools and tactics, along with best practices and strategies.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 p-4 my-6">
            <p class="text-sm text-amber-900 font-semibold mb-2">Update - October 2023:</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-amber-800">
              Major CBC players are shutting down or winding down. Notable instructors like Ali Abdaal and Tiago Forte have announced their last cohorts. The market is consolidating and evolving rapidly.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="platform-providers" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">What CBC Platform Providers Do</h2>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            A CBC platform provider, like Pupilfirst, provides instructors the ability to teach their topics online. This is done by giving tutors the necessary tools to reduce friction and operational overhead required to run online courses.
          </p>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            Along with the platform and tooling, a provider should also create the community, marketplace, and payments infrastructure—so that more people can start their courses and realize their vision for what their school will look like.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="core-areas" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Core Focus Areas for CBC Platforms</h2>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-6">
            Platform providers must focus on the pain points that tutors face, which fall into four main buckets:
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-8">
            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">1. Tooling</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
                Currently, tutors running CBCs are cobbling together low-cost tools:
              </p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 mb-4">
                <li>Teachable for course management</li>
                <li>Slack or Circle for community</li>
                <li>Zoom for video-conferencing</li>
                <li>Dropbox/Google Drive for content hosting</li>
                <li>Email to stitch it all together</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
                This leads to handling endless logistical questions: how do I login, where do I find the most recent lecture, which tasks to submit next, etc. Running a CBC becomes an operational nightmare.
              </p>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                <strong>Pain points can be classified by:</strong>
              </p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 mt-2">
                <li><strong>Magnitude:</strong> Catastrophic issues that need immediate fixing</li>
                <li><strong>Frequency:</strong> Minor frustrations that happen repeatedly (e.g., every lecture)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">2. Pedagogy Support</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">Critical questions tutors need help answering:</p>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-slate-700 mb-6">
                <li>What's the best way to teach a particular subject/topic?</li>
                <li>What sequence should the subject matter be taught in?</li>
                <li>What parts make sense in lecture format?</li>
                <li>How much context do students need before switching to project-based learning?</li>
                <li>How do you shift toward 'learning by doing'?</li>
                <li>How do you translate content into discussion prompts?</li>
                <li>How do you balance structure with flexibility?</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-4">
                <p class="text-sm font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">Example: State Change Method of Live Lectures</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-blue-800 mb-2">For batch sizes of 20-30 students:</p>
                <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-1 text-sm text-blue-800">
                  <li>Talk for 3 mins</li>
                  <li>Ask something in chat, get students to answer</li>
                  <li>Talk for another 3 mins</li>
                  <li>Breakout for 5-10 mins</li>
                  <li>Resume lecture, talk for 5 mins</li>
                  <li>Pop up a question, get students to unmute and chime in</li>
                </ol>
                <p class="text-sm text-blue-700 mt-2 italic">
                  This speeds up the rhythm and makes sessions more dynamic.
                </p>
              </div>

              <p class="text-slate-700 mt-4">
                Platforms must provide course templates, resource libraries, live examples, and expose teachers to different teaching frameworks—helping them avoid common mistakes and build on proven practices.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">3. Access to Teaching Assistants</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                As courses scale, instructors need reliable teaching assistants to maintain quality feedback loops and student support. Platforms should facilitate TA recruitment and management.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">4. Marketing of Courses</h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                Building the course is just part 1. Marketing the course and filling it is part 2. Platforms should support instructors with student acquisition infrastructure and best practices.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="who-can-build" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Who Can Build a Good CBC?</h2>

          <ul class="space-y-4 text-slate-700">
            <li>
              <strong>Subject Matter Experts (SMEs)</strong> with ecosystem credibility and an existing following are best suited to launch CBCs
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Remember:</strong> Building the course is just part 1. Marketing and filling it is part 2. Think of these together—you don't want to invest heavily in building a course only to realize no one wants to buy it.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Your course is your product.</strong> Build only after talking to prospective students and validating your assumptions.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Solve for signaling:</strong> Associating with an accreditation body can help. Individuals with enough ecosystem clout who can secure partnerships with established institutions have a significant advantage.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <div class="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 p-4 my-6">
            <p class="text-sm text-green-900 font-semibold mb-2">The Goal:</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-green-800">
              CBCs should create an immersive learning experience that instills hope—hope that gives students the energy and positive affirmations they need to get through hard parts. Students should feel they've truly learned the subject and had a transformative experience.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="instructor-roles" class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">Roles of a CBC Instructor</h2>

          <p class="text-slate-700 mb-4">
            A CBC instructor tends to play multiple roles simultaneously:
          </p>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-3">
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Teacher</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Coach</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Writer</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Designer</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Consultant</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Manager</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Coordinator</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Editor</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Lecturer</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Preacher</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Tutor</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Systems Integrator</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Performer</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Producer</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Comedian</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Storyteller</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Oracle</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Guru</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Leader</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Guide</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Hacker</div>
            <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Researcher</div>
